2. the arch is slightly hard and uncomfortable on the top of the head, and
3. both the usb charging and auxiliary cables are too short for my liking. The USB charging is less than 2 feet and the auxiliary cable is about 4 feet long.
Others have said that it is uncomfortable on the ears. I have not used it for long periods of time, but I can see how the factors 1 and 2 can make it an uncomfortable experience to wear it for an hour or longer.

column4: Stopped Pairing With Transmitters - Had them Less than A Month! (Update in Review)
column6:
**Update Below**
These headphones are testing my patience. Let me start with the good then I'll talk about the bad.
Pros: They're pretty comfortable, they weren't that expensive, they look nice and feel sturdy.
Cons: They stop pairing with my bluetooth transmitters. I have 2 different brands of transmitters and for some reason these headphones will pair with one, work for a few hours then boom, it won't pair again. I've tried making sure both headphones and transmitters were fully charged but it's a no-go. The headphones like one-night stands with my transmitters. It will work once or twice then never again. I can't tell you how many times I've tried pairing these with the two transmitters I have and it just doesn't work. Then eventually, I can't even get the headphones to pair at all! It goes from Power On to Power Off.
Completely useless if I can't use the wireless option of these headphones. I'm very disappointed.
Update: The company sent me a replacement and it's been working great! I'm able to pair it with no issues. The first pair has again began pairing with my computer's blue tooth but still won't pair with my bluetooth transmitters but that's okay since the new pair works fine.

column4: - I've tried a couple of other similar Bluetooth headphones - not comfortable - and I sent them back to Amazon (like ...
column6:
I don't usually write reviews here on Amazon.  But this product deserves 5 or more stars.  Why I am so excited?
- I've tried a couple of other similar Bluetooth headphones - not comfortable - and I sent them back to Amazon (like Tkqa).  Tried my son's Beat headphones as a benchmark (selling for $100+) for judging others.
- These headphones beats the Beats, hands down, and these are just 1/5 the price.
- More importantly: they are really, really comfortable.  Now, I think this is a personal preference, and depends on your own anatomy (my ear is not your ear!).  I think that this is the most important in getting earbuds, so make sure they fit YOUR ear!  But of all the earbuds I tried, these are the best: they stay in my ear when exercising/running and do not give me any discomfort.  But, your ear may be different from mine ...
- The bass on these headphones is really good. I am an audiophile, and I think the most of the spectrum frequency sounds OK, for little earbuds like these.
- The controls are also good, although I think that the Power On/Power off (also used to answer calls, etc.) is a bit too big.  That is, if I want to reposition the earbuds, I may end up inadvertently switch them off by touching the Power Off button.
- Overall, I think anyone should try these earbuds.  They are a great value for the money and sound the best from all the ones I heard.  If you don't like them, send them back!  (like I did for the many other ones it tried - but this is a winner!)

I've owned this charger for about 20 days and it seems to work well. It came with a QC 3.0 charging brick that was questionable. On first use, it worked OK. After moving it a couple of times, I noticed that it sparked at the wall outlet when I wiggled or moved the brick (to the point that I was concerned if it was going to be a possible fire hazard). The brick died at about 15 days. I've used a 2.0 charger instead and that seems to work OK, although I doubt it charges as fast as the 3.0. I charge the phone overnight, so it doesn't really matter. I contacted the re-seller. He had no spare power bricks to cross ship so he just refunded me the difference in price between this and the charger that comes without the brick.

column4: Don't take your ears for granted.  Protect them with these muffs before you have hearing loss.
column6:
I was shocked and worried when the telephone-based National Hearing Test (free though AARP) revealed my hearing in both ears was slightly below expected for my age.  Although my lawn mower and leaf blower might contribute, the most likely culprit is noisy equipment (air purifier, dehumidifier, security camera NVR) that runs almost 24/7 in the house I purchased two years ago.  The Mpow Ear Muffs are significantly more effective and more comfortable than two brands of ear plugs I've tried, without ear canal irritation or infection risk.  The only downside is that the muffs are so tight for my large head that extended use causes my mild TMJ to ache.
Get your hearing tested and protect your ears with ear muffs, ear plugs and esp. by avoidance of prolonged loud noise exposure.  I should have been more careful starting decades ago, but it's never too late to improve.
